- `gh release edit 1.4.0 --notes-file /tmp/release-1.4.0-notes.md`
- `gh release edit 1.4.1 --notes-file /tmp/release-1.4.1-notes.md`

[mistakes and lessons]
- I originally created the retrospective releases with `gh release create --notes "..."` and embedded `\\n` escapes inside a shell string. GitHub stored those characters literally instead of converting them into line breaks.
- For future releases, do not rely on escaped newline sequences inside shell strings for release notes. Use one of:
  - `--notes-file <path>` with a prepared markdown file,
  - a here-doc piped into a file first,
  - or another workflow that passes real multiline text, not escaped sequences.
- This is the same class of failure as earlier shell-escaping mistakes: when formatting matters, prefer file-backed input over inline quoted strings.

