[observations]
- The project has strong architectural foundations after 1.5.0 modularization but lacks formal compliance documentation.
- 30 open issues now exist, creating a clear roadmap for the next 3-5 months of development.
- Security vulnerabilities (CVE-2026-39892) require immediate attention and are now tracked in issue #135.
- The new layout.html provides a foundation for consistent UI/UX but requires migration of existing templates.
- Compliance issues (#163-#173) represent significant work (estimated 8-12 weeks) but are essential for enterprise adoption.
- GitHub issues provide better tracking than kimi-milestones.txt, but the text file serves as a reference for offline planning.
- The analysis revealed that the project is operationally mature (production deployments) but needs hardening for compliance-sensitive environments.

[decisions]
- Create three separate documentation files (proposals, prompts, milestones) rather than one monolithic document to serve different use cases.
- Prioritize security vulnerabilities (#135-#137) over feature development.
- Map compliance requirements to specific NIST/ISO controls for audit traceability.
- Keep layout.html backward compatible by not forcing migration of existing templates immediately.
- Use GitHub milestones as the source of truth for scheduling, with kimi-milestones.txt as supplementary detail.
- Focus compliance issues on practical implementation rather than documentation-only, as the project needs executable controls, not just policies.

[mistakes and lessons]
- Initially attempted to create all issues in parallel, which led to label creation errors (priority:low didn't exist).
  Lesson: Create prerequisite resources (labels) before dependent operations (issues with those labels).
- The layout.html rewrite could break existing templates if they depend on specific CSS classes.
  Lesson: Document breaking changes and provide migration guide in the issue (#155).
- Some compliance issues (#163-#173) overlap with existing functionality (audit logging exists but needs integrity).
  Lesson: Explicitly distinguish between "missing feature" and "enhancement to existing feature" in issue descriptions.

